[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Hey, welcome back to the channel. Well, we all know that we can now do just about anything we imagined using AI. Okay, not what I meant. I hate spiders. Could we please use any other example? Okay, well, once you get past all the'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'razledazzle of all the cool effects we can do with AI, quality is still going to come down to a good story. And one of the most essential elements in storytelling can be dialogue. And I think a lot of people just sort of throw'

[00:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'dialogue into their AI productions without giving it a lot of thought because maybe they aren\'t writers and they\'re just trying to do movie trailers or whatever. Now, I\'m not saying I\'m the best writer in the whole wide world, but I am inviting you to play with the abilities that the newest AI models have'

[00:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'when it comes to realistic dialogue and being able to portray real emotions that draw you in. I know you\'re hearing a lot about Cling 3 recently, and you may be a little tired of it, but it happens to do this very well. And I want to walk you'

[00:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'through a couple of scenes that have very short lines of dialogue, but depending on how you prompt it, can convey completely different emotions. And these are the types of things that as a storyteller, you\'re going to want to play with and get good at. &gt;&gt; I didn\'t think you\'re going to show up.'

[01:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I didn\'t think you\'re going to show up. &gt;&gt; As I walk you through these examples, you\'re going to see how minor changes to the dialogue and the addition of specific camera cuts can change the mood of the entire scene. All of these'

[01:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'examples today were done with the Cling 3 Omni model so that I could use these consistent characters through all of these generations. Using Cling 3 also gives us access to its multi-shot capability just within the prompting itself to make the scene look more'

[01:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'interesting. All of these prompts evolved over time as you will see in both the action, the camera angles, and the dialogue that\'s being said. But here\'s what it started out with. &gt;&gt; I didn\'t think you\'re going to show up. &gt;&gt; I wasn\'t going to.'

[01:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; So why are you here? I like the coffee. &gt;&gt; So, let\'s look at the initial prompt. We\'ve got the two characters sitting across from each other in a diner, much'

[01:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'like the movie Heat. I refer to that specifically. They each have a cup of coffee in front of them, and they are having a conversational exchange that is flirty but intense. So, flirty and intense are both prompted in here. The woman says, "I didn\'t think you were'

[02:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'going to show up." And then the man says, "I wasn\'t going to." Now, I leave it up to the AI to determine how each of them are going to say that given the undertones that I\'ve suggested. The woman stares at him for a second and says, "So why are you here?" So adding that second before she spoke was'

[02:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'important to create that tension. Then the man pauses, looks around, and says, "I like the coffee." The woman looks at him for a second and smiles slightly. We have a very clear tone, and we can kind of fill in a backstory. They\'re dressed like they\'re both on some sort of a'

[02:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mission. They\'ve met here at this coffee shop. They\'ve obviously got a history, and they\'re both trying to play it real cool, but obviously there\'s a little bit of a spark. But let\'s see how this evolves. &gt;&gt; I didn\'t think you\'re going to show up. I wasn\'t going to.'

[02:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; So, why are you here? &gt;&gt; I like the coffee. &gt;&gt; That was the exact same prompt except for the last line about what kind of music was playing in the background, but the AI gave it a little bit of a'

[02:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'different spin. The flirty flirt isn\'t quite so overt. To shake things up both visually and with the tone, I added some camera angles, and these camera angles will suggest certain emotions that these actors portray pretty well. Once I\'ve'

[03:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'described the conversational exchange they\'re having as flirty and intense, I now say cut to a closeup of Tracy saying, "I didn\'t think you were going to show up." And then cut to the bounty hunter guy saying, "I wasn\'t going to." Now we have a POV of Tracy over the'

[03:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'shoulder of the bounty hunter. She stares at him for a second and says, "Then why are you here?" Cut to a medium shot of both of them. And then he says, "I like the coffee." And she smiles slightly. So let\'s see what that looks like.'

[03:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; I didn\'t think you\'re going to show up. I wasn\'t going to. &gt;&gt; So, why are you here? &gt;&gt; I like the coffee. Now, I think you\'ll agree that even though we changed none of the dialogue, just changing those'

[03:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'camera angles changed the feel of the scene. And I\'m loving the different tones and timing of the guy\'s initial response. &gt;&gt; I didn\'t think you\'re going to show up. &gt;&gt; I wasn\'t going to. &gt;&gt; So, he\'s got a big pause there. Whereas'

[03:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with this previous clip, although there\'s a pause, it\'s not the kind of pause where he\'s thinking about it. &gt;&gt; I didn\'t think you\'re going to show up. &gt;&gt; I wasn\'t going to. This example, everything is the same except that I added back the all the while sultry jazz'

[04:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'music is playing in the background. Let\'s see how you think it affected the tone. &gt;&gt; I didn\'t think you\'re going to show up. &gt;&gt; I wasn\'t going to. &gt;&gt; So, why are you here? &gt;&gt; I like the coffee.'

[04:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; Specifically, again, look at the guy\'s reaction. &gt;&gt; I didn\'t think you\'re going to show up. &gt;&gt; I wasn\'t going to. &gt;&gt; He\'s got that little Now, what are you going to say?'

[04:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; So, why are you here? I like the coffee. &gt;&gt; Having this intense close-up of her reacting to him definitely says a lot in terms of the emotions that are going on between them. Here, we added one line at the end and it changes the overall tone'

[04:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of the whole thing because instead of just smiling at him slightly, she verbalizes the word okay. &gt;&gt; I didn\'t think you\'re going to show up. &gt;&gt; I wasn\'t going to. &gt;&gt; So, why are you here?'

[05:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; I like the coffee. Okay. &gt;&gt; So, in that last little move, you could tell she wanted him to say something else and he didn\'t say it and she\'s not liking it. So, she\'s getting a little'

[05:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'snippy. Her reaction at the end of that last generation inspired me to really lean into how upset she\'s getting with this and how snarky she\'s going to be. So, at the end of this whole exchange, where last time she just said okay, instead she says, "Okay, well, I don\'t,'

[05:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'so I\'m going to leave." And now she starts to get up and we cut to a twoot. And now the bounty hunter guy is grabbing her arm and saying, "No, wait." And then she looks at him and snaps sarcastically. Oh, I\'m sorry. Was there'

[05:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'something else besides the coffee? So, let\'s see what that looks like. &gt;&gt; I didn\'t think you\'re going to show up. &gt;&gt; I wasn\'t going to. &gt;&gt; So, why are you here? &gt;&gt; I like the coffee.'

[05:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; Okay. Well, I don\'t, so I\'m besigned to leave. &gt;&gt; No, wait. &gt;&gt; Oh, I\'m sorry. Was there something else besides the coffee? Aside from the fact that we get that lip sync drift that we do on these longer clips with Clling, the journey that we went through with'

[06:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'her facial expressions when she reacted to him saying he liked the coffee was amazing. &gt;&gt; Okay. Well, I don\'t. So, I\'m besigned to leave. &gt;&gt; No, wait. &gt;&gt; Like, yikes. I would not want to be on the other side of that table here. I'

[06:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'didn\'t change anything. It\'s just another generation. &gt;&gt; I didn\'t think you\'re going to show up. &gt;&gt; I wasn\'t going to. &gt;&gt; So, why are you here? &gt;&gt; I like the coffee. &gt;&gt; Okay. Well, I don\'t. So, I\'m going to leave.'

[06:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'No, wait. &gt;&gt; Oh, I\'m sorry. Was there something else beside the coffee? &gt;&gt; Last example with this scenario, but what she does with her nose. &gt;&gt; I didn\'t think you\'re going to show up. &gt;&gt; I wasn\'t going to.'

[06:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; So, why are you here? &gt;&gt; I like the coffee. &gt;&gt; Okay. Well, I don\'t, so I\'m going to leave. &gt;&gt; No, wait. &gt;&gt; Oh, I\'m sorry. Was there something else besides the coffee?'

[06:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; I really love that except for the lip-sync mismatch at the end. Here we have another piece of dialogue that suggests a lot of backstory and a lot of underlying emotions and a really good opportunity to see inside the mind of these characters who are cartoons. So'

[07:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'once again, we have a couple in a restaurant. We have the scientist guy and a woman who does change throughout these examples who are sitting close next to each other in a dark restaurant booth. The scientist guy looks at the woman and says, "You know, you really'

[07:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'screwed up my life by coming back." And we cut to the woman who\'s coily saying, "Yeah, I know." And then cut to a twoot as they kiss and she whispers in his ear, "So, what do you want to do about it?"'

[07:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; You know, you really screwed up my life by coming back. &gt;&gt; Yeah, I know. So, what do you want to do about it? &gt;&gt; So, in this example, he\'s happy. She\'s'

[07:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'happy. I think we all know what they\'re going to do about it. &gt;&gt; You know, you really screwed up my life by coming back. &gt;&gt; Yeah. I know.'

[07:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; So, what do you want to do about it? &gt;&gt; What\'s crazy about that one, and this is just a little piece of trivia, is that this character is based on Tracy, and that eye up to the right thing is'

[08:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'something she does. I have no idea how it knew to do that. &gt;&gt; You know, you really screwed up my life by coming back. &gt;&gt; Yeah, I know. So, what do you want to do about it?'

[08:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; Dude, you need to run. &gt;&gt; You know, you really screwed up my life by coming back. &gt;&gt; Yeah, I know. &gt;&gt; So, what do you want to do about it?'

[08:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; So, you can see the facial expression in this scene is very different. He\'s not so sure. He\'s not necessarily so happy. He knows he\'s in a tricky situation. And this girl is probably up to no good. You know, you really screwed up my life by'

[08:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'coming back. &gt;&gt; Yeah, I know. &gt;&gt; So, what do you want to do about it? &gt;&gt; All of these examples, everything has'

[09:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'been exactly the same, and it\'s given us a slightly different read on every single one of them. Just like if you were working with two real actors on a set and you said, "Okay, do it this way. Do it this way. Do it this way." And in my mind, the AI is doing a tremendous'

[09:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'job of picking up exactly what this scene is putting down. In this example, I changed one word. Instead of saying, "So, what do you want to do about it?" at the end, she says, "So, what do you want to do about that?" And that changes it.'

[09:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; You know, you really screwed up my life by coming back. &gt;&gt; Yeah, I know. &gt;&gt; So, what do you want to do about that? &gt;&gt; Don\'t you think so? So, as you continue'

[09:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'your creative AI journey and you make your short films and your trailers and all your other stuff, consider this an invitation to give special consideration to the dialogue and the emotional undertones going on with the characters in the scene because at the end of the'

[09:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'day, that is what is going to engage an audience more than explosions and other special effects. If these are the types of things you like to get an insight on, well, why not subscribe to this channel? Because this is the kind of stuff we talk about all the time.'

